## While You Work

### Code Standards

- **Naming**: camelCase (vars/functions), PascalCase (classes/types), UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (constants), kebab-case (files)
- **Files**: One main export per file, tests co-located with `.test.ts` suffix
- **Comments**: JSDoc for public APIs, inline for complex logic, skip the obvious
- **Types**: Strict TypeScript, no `any` without justification

### Architecture Rules

- **Three-layer purity**: No business logic in runtime layer, no UI in capability layer
- **Simplicity first**: Minimum code that solves the problem. No speculative abstractions. See `.claude/rules/karpathy-principles.md` Principle 2.
- **Surgical changes**: Touch only what you must. Don't "improve" adjacent code. See `.claude/rules/karpathy-principles.md` Principle 3.
- **Zero-conflict**: Tool name prefixes mandatory (`memory-*`, `review-*`, etc.)
- **Stateless services**: Capability layer services are stateless; state goes to MemoryService

### When to Stop

**Do NOT declare victory until:**

1. ✅ All tests pass (`npm test` or `npx vitest run`)
2. ✅ Lint clean (`npx eslint .`)
3. ✅ Type check passes (`npx tsc --noEmit`)
4. ✅ ReviewEngine Layer 1-2 pass (auto-fixable issues resolved)
5. ✅ Feature verification: The feature actually works as described in `feature_list.json`

### Anti-Rationalization Table

> 基于 Agent Skills (https://github.com/addyosmani/agent-skills) 的反借口机制。
> Agent 倾向于走"最短路径"，跳过"麻烦事"。以下是常见借口及反驳。

| Excuse | Reality |
|--------|---------|
| "It's working, no need to touch it" | Working code that's hard to read will be hard to fix when it breaks. Simplifying now saves time on every future change. |
| "I'll write tests after the code works" | You won't. And tests written after the fact test implementation, not behavior. Write the failing test first. |
| "This is too simple to test" | Simple code gets complicated. The test documents the expected behavior. |
| "I tested it manually" | Manual testing doesn't persist. Tomorrow's change might break it with no way to know. |
| "We'll optimize later" | Performance debt compounds. Fix obvious anti-patterns now, defer micro-optimizations only after measurement. |
| "It's fast on my machine" | Your machine isn't the user's. Profile on representative hardware and networks. |
| "Fewer lines is always simpler" | A 1-line nested ternary is not simpler than a 5-line if/else. Simplicity is about comprehension speed, not line count. |
| "I'll just quickly simplify this unrelated code too" | Unscoped simplification creates noisy diffs and risks regressions. Stay focused on the assigned feature. |
| "The types make it self-documenting" | Types document structure, not intent. A well-named function explains *why* better than a type signature explains *what*. |
| "This abstraction might be useful later" | Don't preserve speculative abstractions. If it's not used now, it's complexity without value. Remove it and re-add when needed. |
| "The original author must have had a reason" | Maybe. Check git blame — apply Chesterton's Fence. But accumulated complexity often has no reason; it's just residue of iteration under pressure. |
| "I'll refactor while adding this feature" | Separate refactoring from feature work. Mixed changes are harder to review, revert, and understand in history. |
| "Tests slow me down" | Tests slow you down now. They speed you up every time you change the code later. |
| "It's just a prototype" | Prototypes become production code. Tests and specs from day one prevent the "debt" crisis. |

